In this posting:
[1] Bacterial wilt, rhizome rot - Jamaica
[2] Soft rot, leaf spot - India (Karnataka)

******
[1] Bacterial wilt, rhizome rot - Jamaica
Date: Mon 12 Mar 2012
Source: Jamaica Information Service [edited]
http://74.54.30.150/news/list/30019


The Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries [MAF] has been providing support for ginger cultivation and made a commitment to plant some 150 acres [60 ha] of ginger and 350 acres [140 ha] of turmeric this year [2012]. Jamaican ginger production declined from some 900 mt per year during the 1990's to 298 mt in 2008, largely due to the impact of 2 major plant diseases -- bacterial wilt and rhizome rot.

The national short-term production target of 21 000 mt of fresh ginger requires approximately 3000 cultivated acres [1200 ha, as well as] disease-free ginger planting material of about 2700 mt per year. Given the impact of diseases on the industry, MAF has been evaluating the production of disease-free planting material using a combination of tissue culture, protected environment and hydroponic technologies. These trials have performed credibly.

For 2012, the ginger development project will specifically target acreage expansion in areas with minimal disease impact; husbandry improvements in areas that show signs of disease; and commercial production of disease-free ginger planting material.

